{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":28001,"record_hash":"sha256:9c5efa29b4430b9c1aa9cc33fee472fc4ae917a7135c02e5421aa5893a40bf9f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T12:23:05.270Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Findings:\\n\\n- [P2] [capture.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/capture.rs:17) returns `has_records.then_some(session_key)` while the tuple type is just `(usize, Option<String>)`. Here `Option<String>` really means “association-safe session key from any recognized transcript record, even when `records_written == 0` after dedupe.” That subtle distinction is central to the new skip-session/other behavior and is easy to regress to `records_written > 0`; consider a named result field or more domain-specific local name than `has_records`.\\n\\n- [P2] [cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:236) protects association after a no-new-record capture, but the helper it relies on is named generically as `write_transcript` at [cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:300). Because the helper must include at least one capturable message record for this behavior to work, the test is brittle against a “simplification” back to session metadata only. A name like `write_transcript_with_message` or an inline fixture would make the new skip-session rule obvious.\\n\\n- [P3] [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:495) only checks that an empty transcript creates no session metadata. There is no focused test for the more important new edge case: a transcript with only skipped `session_meta`/`other` records should also create no metadata and should not associate. That gap matters because the parser now intentionally extracts metadata from skipped records while persistence depends on recognized timeline records.\\n\\nValidation: `cargo test -p but-agentlog` passes.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T12:23:05.270Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"Findings:\\n\\n- [P2] [capture.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/capture.rs:17) returns `has_records.then_some(session_key)` while the tuple type is just `(usize, Option<String>)`. Here `Option<String>` really means “association-safe session key from any recognized transcript record, even when `records_written == 0` after dedupe.” That subtle distinction is central to the new skip-session/other behavior and is easy to regress to `records_written > 0`; consider a named result field or more domain-specific local name than `has_records`.\\n\\n- [P2] [cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:236) protects association after a no-new-record capture, but the helper it relies on is named generically as `write_transcript` at [cli.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:300). Because the helper must include at least one capturable message record for this behavior to work, the test is brittle against a “simplification” back to session metadata only. A name like `write_transcript_with_message` or an inline fixture would make the new skip-session rule obvious.\\n\\n- [P3] [gitmeta.rs](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:495) only checks that an empty transcript creates no session metadata. There is no focused test for the more important new edge case: a transcript with only skipped `session_meta`/`other` records should also create no metadata and should not associate. That gap matters because the parser now intentionally extracts metadata from skipped records while persistence depends on recognized timeline records.\\n\\nValidation: `cargo test -p but-agentlog` passes.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>"}]}}}